Raw dev notes -- NotebookLM ChatWrapper: The Browser-as-Runtime Journey (late March 2026)

This week I mass-refactored my NotebookLM API wrapper. The old approach extracted cookies
and replayed them with httpx -- fragile, broke every few hours. The new idea: keep a
persistent headless Playwright browser running and execute all Google API calls INSIDE it
via page.evaluate(fetch). The browser IS the session.

Key commits/milestones:
- Replaced custom httpx client with notebooklm-py SDK
- Built native auth via storage_state.json + automated session refresh
- Moved to browser-as-runtime: all RPC calls via persistent Playwright page.evaluate(fetch)
- Added stealth mode + real Chrome channel to dodge bot detection
- Built a 24h endurance test with simulated user messages across two notebooks
- Handled Google account chooser in auto-login flow
- Fixed corrupt browser cache on startup

Struggles:
- CSRF tokens expire unpredictably. I tried refreshing every 25-35min with jitter
- Auto-retry on RPC error with rebuilt client was tricky -- had to distinguish auth vs transient errors
- Periodic page refresh killed the session instead of keeping it alive (counterintuitive!)
- Google login selectors kept changing -- had to make email/password button selectors robust

Reflection: The key insight is that fighting Google's auth system is futile. Instead of
extracting tokens, just let the browser handle everything natively. It's like the difference
between reverse-engineering an API and just using the website. Sometimes the "lazy" approach
is the smart one.

Next: Session refresh on heartbeat timeouts, source pipeline, concurrent user support.
